The crystal structure and phase composition data are depicted in 
                     Fig. 4
                     a. All the samples exhibit high crystallinity and purity. Commercial Nb2AlC MAX powder displayed its characteristic peaks based on JCPDS 20–0101, with the presence of Al characterized by the prominent band at (103) plane at 2θ = 38.8°. This peak was not found after the etching process, indicating successful removal of Al to form Nb2CTx material. The complete transformation of MAX phase into MXene was also confirmed by the leftward shift and broadening of another prominent peak of (002) plane from 12.78° to 7.58°, indicating increased interlayer spacing due to the loss of Al layers. The presence of two diffraction peaks observed at 40.8°and 35.2° corresponds to (200) and (111) planes of niobium carbide (Nb2C) phase, a typical formation of Nb2AlC, which is commonly observed in Nb2CTx MXene [31]. After combining rGQDs, no alteration was observed in the peaks, suggesting that rGQDs did not induce any structural changes in UiO-66, a finding corroborated by FE-SEM results. Upon combining Nb2CTx with UiO-66@rGQDs, the characteristic peak of Nb2CTx at 7.58° emerged in the spectrum of UiO-66@rGQDs, confirming their successful integration. Raman spectra of Nb2AlC, Nb2CTx, UiO-66, UiO-66@rGQDs, and Nb2CTx/UiO-66@rGQDs illustrated in Fig. 4
                     b and S4 display two characteristic broad peaks at 1348 and 1588 cm−1 (D and G peaks) of Nb2CTx, UiO-66@rGQDs, and Nb2CTx/UiO-66@rGQDs. The G band corresponds to planar vibrations of sp2 hybridized carbon atoms, while the D band is indicative of the disordered structures and defect associated with sp3 hybridized carbon atoms. The wavenumber of D and G peaks in Nb2CTx were shifted and broadened compared to Nb2AlC, which indicated strengthening of the bond between atoms (Fig. S4
                     ). The ID/IG values of Nb2AlC and Nb2CTx were 1.23, and 1.01, respectively. Moreover, the disappeared peak at 400 cm−1 (Fig. S4
                     ) after etching MAX to MXene could be due to the disappearing of Al-C bonds or exchange of Al atoms by the lighter atoms [32]. The characteristic bands of Nb2O5 at 233 cm−1 represent the orthorhombic phase, indicating that Nb2O5 existed (see Fig. S4) [33]. The peak at 1615 cm−1 is assigned to UiO-66 structure, which is present in the spectra of both UiO-66@rGQDs and Nb2CTx/UiO-66@rGQDs. After combining Nb2CTx with UiO-66@rGQDs, the peak at 1615 cm−1 was shifted towards the left, illustrating a strong interaction between them during the synthesis process, supporting successful etching of Nb2CTx and synthesis of Nb2CTx/UiO-66@rGQDs.

Fig. 5
c shows the PL spectroscopy of Nb2CTx, GO, UiO-66, rGQDs, UiO-66@rGQDs, Nb2CTx/UiO-66@rGQDs, revealing charge separation efficiency of the catalysts. The introduction of rGQDs in UiO-66@rGQDs played an effective role, as indicated by the decrease in PL emission intensity compared to pristine UiO-66 and rGQDs, suggesting reduced recombination of photogenerated electron-hole pairs, thereby confirming the enhanced charge separation efficiency due to rGQD incorporation (see Fig. S5e
). Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) was also performed to confirm the role of rGQDs in improving electronic properties and photocatalytic efficiency of UiO-66@rGQDs. As presented in Fig. S5f, the EIS spectra demonstrate a reduced charge transfer resistance for UiO-66@rGQDs composite compared to pristine UiO-66, further confirming the role of rGQDs in boosting the conductivity. The PL emission intensity of Nb2CTx/UiO-66@rGQDs significantly reduced compared to UiO-66@rGQDs, UiO-66, and rGQDs due to the suppressive effect of Nb2CTx on charge recombination, thereby highlighting its role in enhancing the photocatalytic efficiency. The observed prominent red shift from 306 nm of pure UiO-66@rGQDs to 395 nm for Nb2CTx/UiO-66@rGQD nanocomposites for absorption edge values (Fig. S6
) improved the photocatalytic performance [36].
